# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-almanac
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-almanac] It serves, in turn, as a source for a number of books and publications about baseball, and/or is mentioned by them as a reference, such as *Baseball Digest*, *Understanding Sabermetrics: An Introduction to the Science of Baseball Statistics*, and *Baseball's Top 100: The Game's Greatest Records*.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-almanac] Dan Zachofsky described it in *Collecting Baseball Memorabilia: A Handbook* as having the most current information regarding members of the Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-almanac] David Maraniss, author of *Clemente, the Passion and Grace of Baseball's Last Hero*, described it as "an absolutely reliable and first-rate bountiful source, that supplied accurate schedules and box scores".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-almanac] Glenn Guzo, in *The New Ballgame: Baseball Statistics for the Casual Fan*, described it as having "a rich supply of contemporary and historic information".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-almanac] Film critic Richard Roeper described it in *Sox and the City: A Fan's Love Affair with the White Sox from the Heartbreak of '67 to the Wizards of Oz* as "one of the beauteous wonders of the Internet".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-almanac] Harvey Frommer, Dartmouth College Professor and sports author, said of *Baseball Almanac*: "Definitive, vast in its reach and scope, *Baseball Almanac* is a mother lode of facts, figures, anecdotes, quotations and essays focused on the national pastime....
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The question of the origins of baseball has been the subject of debate and controversy for more than a century.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Baseball and the other modern bat, ball, and running games – stoolball, cricket and rounders – were developed from folk games in early Great Britain, Ireland, and Continental Europe (such as France and Germany).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Early forms of baseball had a number of names, including "base ball", "goal ball", "round ball", "fetch-catch", "stool ball", and, simply, "base".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In at least one version of the game, teams pitched to themselves, runners went around the bases in the opposite direction of today's game, much like in the Nordic brännboll, and players could be put out by being hit with the ball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Just as now, in some versions a batter was called out after three strikes.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Although much is unclear, as one would expect of children's games of long ago, this much is known: by the mid-18th century a game had appeared in Southern England, which involved striking a pitched ball and then running a circuit of bases set out in a diamond pattern.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Base-Ball is referenced in 1744 in the children's book *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book* English colonists took this game to North America with their other pastimes, and in the early 1800s variants were being played on both sides of the ocean under many appellations.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] However, the game was very significantly altered by amateur men's ball clubs in and around New York City in the middle of the 19th century, and it was this heavily revised sport that became modern baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A number of folk games in early Britain and continental Europe had characteristics that can be seen in modern baseball (as well as in cricket and rounders).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Many of these early games involved a ball that was thrown at a target while an opposing player defended the target by attempting to hit the ball away.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] If the batter successfully hit the ball, he could attempt to score points by running between bases while fielders would attempt to catch or retrieve the ball and put the runner out.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Folk games differed over time, place, and culture, resulting in similar yet variant forms.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] These games had no standard documented rules and instead were played according to historical customs.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] These games tended to be played by working classes, peasants, and children.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Early folk games were often associated with earlier religious ceremonies and worship rituals.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] These games became discouraged and even altogether prohibited by subsequent governing states and religious authorities.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Very broadly speaking, these games can be roughly divided into forms of *longball*, where the batter ran out to a single point or line and back, as in cricket, and *roundball*, where there was a circuit of multiple bases.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There were also games (e.g. stool-ball, trap-ball) which involved no running at all.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Oină is a Romanian traditional sport, a form of longball similar in many ways to lapta.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The name "oină" was originally "hoina", and is derived from the Cuman word *oyn* "game" (a cognate of Turkish *oyun*).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The oldest direct mention comes from 1364.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In 1899, Spiru Haret, the minister of education decided that oină was to be played in schools in physical education classes.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] He organized the first annual oină competitions.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Romanian Oină Federation ("*Federaţia Română de Oină*") was founded in 1932, and was reactivated at the beginning of the 1950s, after a brief period when it was dissolved.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Today, there are two oină federations: one in Bucharest, Romania and another one in Chişinău, Moldova.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In an 1802 book entitled *The Sports and Pastimes of the People of England*, Joseph Strutt claimed to have shown that baseball-like games can be traced back to the 14th century, in particular an English game called stoolball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The earliest known reference to stoolball is in a 1330 poem by William Pagula, who recommended to priests that the game be forbidden within churchyards.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In stoolball, one player throws the ball at a target while another player defends the target.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Originally, the target was defended with a bare hand.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Later, a bat of some kind was used (in modern stoolball, a bat like a very heavy table tennis paddle is used).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] "Stob-ball" and "stow-ball" were regional games similar to stoolball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] What the target originally was in stoolball is not certain; it was possibly a tree stump, since "*stob*" and "*stow*" all mean *stump* in some local dialects.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] ("*Stow*" could also refer to a type of frame used in mining).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] It is notable that in cricket to this day, the uprights of the wicket are called "stumps".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Of course, the target could well have been whatever was convenient, perhaps even a gravestone (hence Pagula's objection to churchyard play).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A 17th-century book on games specifies a stool.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] According to one legend, milkmaids played stoolball while waiting for their husbands to return from the fields.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Another theory is that stoolball developed as a game played after attending church services, in which case the target was probably a church stool.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] An 18th-century poem depicts men and women playing together (the women using their aprons to catch batted balls), and it and other references associate the game especially with the Easter season.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There were several versions of stoolball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In the earliest versions, the object was primarily to defend the stool.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Successfully defending the stool counted for one point, and the batter was out if the ball hit the stool.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Another version of stoolball involved running between two stools, and scoring was similar to the scoring in cricket.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In perhaps yet another version there were several stools, and points were scored by running around them as in baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] When Englishmen came to America, they brought stoolball with them.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] William Bradford in his diary for Christmas Day, 1621, noted (with disapproval) how the men of Plymouth were "frolicking in þe street, at play openly; some pitching þe barre, some at stoole-ball and shuch-like sport".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Because of the different versions of stoolball, and because it was played not only in England, but also in colonial America, stoolball is considered by many to have been the common ancestor of cricket, baseball and rounders.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In tut-ball or pize-ball, which was similar to both stoolball and rounders, the corners of the infield were marked by "tuts" (sods or pieces of brick that marked the bases) rather than stools, and the batter generally hit with their hand.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Another early folk game was "dog and cat" (or "cat and dog"), which probably originated in Scotland.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In cat and dog an oblong piece of wood called a *cat* is thrown at a hole in the ground while another player defends the hole with a stick (a *dog*).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In some cases there were two holes and, after hitting the cat, the batter would run between them while fielders would try to get the runner out by putting the cat in the hole before the runner got to it.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] This game, otherwise unknown, was described in Francis Willughby's Book of Games (ca.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] 1670), which included rules for over 130 pastimes including stool-ball and stow-ball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] It is significant in that it involved both a bat and base-running, although it was played with a wooden cat rather than a ball and the multiple "bases" were holes in the ground: the batter reached safety by putting the end of his bat in a hole before the fielders could put the cat in it.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] This has echoes in cricket's manner of scoring runs by touching the bat to the ground across the crease before the fielders can hit the nearby wicket with the ball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In trap ball, played in England since the 14th century, a ball was thrown in the air, to be hit by a batsman and fielded.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In trap-ball there was no running, instead the fielders attempted to throw the ball back to within a certain distance of the batter's station.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Trap-ball may be the origin of the concept of foul lines; in most variants the ball had to be hit between two posts to count.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] An old English game called "*base*" or "*prisoners' base*", described by George Ewing at Valley Forge, was apparently not much like baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The game was more like a fancy game of team "tag", although it did share the concept of places of safety, bases, with baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The history of cricket prior to 1650 is something of a mystery.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Games believed to have been similar to cricket had developed by the 13th century.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There was a game called "creag", and another game, "Handyn and Handoute" (Hands In and Hands Out), which was made illegal in 1477 by King Edward IV, who considered the game childish, and a distraction from compulsory archery practice.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] References to a game actually called "*cricket*" appeared around 1550.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The word is etymologically related to French *croquet*- early forms of which were also played with a curved stick rather than a mallet.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The earliest known mention of baseball, as a children's game, dates from the same year (1744) in which the Artillery Ground Laws formalised the rules of what was already a first-class, professional sport sponsored by nobility and upon which vast wagers were laid.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] English colonists played cricket along with their other games from home, and it is mentioned many times in 18th-century American sources.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] As an organized sport, the Toronto Cricket Club was established in that city by 1827 and the St George's Cricket Club was formed in 1838 in New York City (membership restricted to British-born men).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Teams from the two clubs faced off in the first international cricket game in 1844 that Toronto won by 23 runs.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Many of the early New York club baseball players were also cricketers, and the earliest recorded inter-club baseball game was played on the Union Star Cricket Grounds in Brooklyn.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Irish game of rounder is similar to baseball, and most mentioned as its ancestor or nearest relation, is rounders.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Like baseball, the object is to strike a pitched ball with a bat and then run a circuit of four bases to score.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The batter must strike at a good ball and run in an anti-clockwise direction around the first, second, and third base and home to the fourth, though they may stay at any of the first three.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A batter is out if the ball is caught; if the base to which they are running to is touched with the ball; or if, while running, they are touched with the ball by a fielder.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Nine players constitute a team, with the fielding side consisting of the bowler, the backstop (catcher), a player on each of the four bases, and three deep fielders.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Popular among British and Irish school children, and especially among girls, as of 2015 rounders is played by seven million children in the UK.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In 1828, William Clarke in London published the second edition of *The Boy's Own Book*, which included the rules of rounders (in fact the earliest known use of that name), and the first printed description in English of a bat and ball base-running game played on a diamond.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The following year, the book was published in Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A unique British sport, known as British baseball, is still played in parts of Wales and England.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Although confined mainly to the cities of Cardiff, Newport and Liverpool, the sport boasts an annual international game between representative teams from the two countries.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] According to many sources, the earliest appearance of the word "baseball" dates from 1700, when Anglican bishop Thomas Wilson expressed his disapproval of "Morris-dancing, cudgel-playing, baseball and cricket" occurring on Sundays.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] However, David Block, in *Baseball Before We Knew It* (2005), reports that the original source has "stoolball" for "baseball".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Block also reports the reference appears to date to 1672, rather than 1700.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A 1744 book in England by children's publisher John Newbery called *A Little Pretty Pocket-Book* includes a woodcut of a game similar to three-base stoolball or rounders and a rhyme entitled "Base-Ball".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] This is the first known instance of the word baseball in print.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] John Thorn, Major League Baseball's official historian, speculates that the game depicted may have involved hitting the ball with a bare hand, as in punchball, and that hitting with a bat may not have become established until later in the century.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Therefore, *The Card* was the oldest surviving reference to baseball until the Bray diary was discovered in 2008.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The earliest recorded game of base-ball involved the family of the Prince of Wales, played indoors in London in November 1748.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Prince is reported as playing "Bass-Ball" again in September 1749 in Walton-on-Thames, Surrey, against Lord Middlesex.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The English lawyer William Bray wrote in his diary that he had played a game of baseball on Easter Monday 1755 in Guildford, also in Surrey.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] By 1796, the rules of this English game were well enough established to earn a mention in the German Johann Christoph Friedrich GutsMuths' book on popular pastimes.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In it he described "*Ball mit Freystäten (oder das englische Base-ball)*" ('Ball with safe places, or the English base-ball') as a contest between two teams in which "the batter has three attempts to hit the ball while at the home plate"; only one out was required to retire a side.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Gutsmuth included a diagram of the field that was very similar to that of town ball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Notably, Gutsmuths is the earliest author to explicitly mention the use of a bat, although in this case it was a flat wooden paddle about 18 inches long, swung one-handed.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The French book *Les Jeux des Jeunes Garçons* is the second known book to contain printed rules of a batting/base/running game.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] It was printed in Paris in 1810 and lays out the rules for *La balle empoisonnée* ("poisoned ball"), in which there were two teams of eight to ten players, four bases (one called home), a pitcher, a batter, "soaking" and flyball outs; however, the ball apparently was struck by the hand.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Another early print reference is Jane Austen's novel *Northanger Abbey*, originally written 1798–1799.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In the first chapter the young English heroine Catherine Morland is described as preferring "cricket, base ball, riding on horseback and running about the country to books".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] David Block speculates that this version of baseball was also played without a bat.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] About the same time, Austen's cousin Cassandra Cooke mentioned baseball in her novel *Battleridge*.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In 1828, William Clarke of London published the second edition of *The Boy's Own Book*, which included the earliest known mention of a game called "rounders," and contains under that heading the first printed description in English of a bat and ball base-running game played on a diamond.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Similar rules were published in Boston in *The Book of Sports*, written by Robin Carver in 1834, except Carver called the game "Base or Goal ball".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Clarke's "rounders" description would be reprinted many times on both sides of the Atlantic in ensuing decades, under various names.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Although the inclusion of *two* flags marked between the bases on opposite sides of the field suggests the possibility that the batting position alternated, as in cricket.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Charting the evolution of the game that became modern baseball is difficult before 1845.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Knickerbocker Rules describe a game that had been played for some time, but for how long is uncertain.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] One, mostly English, asserted that baseball evolved from a game of English origin (probably rounders); the other, almost entirely American, said that baseball was an American invention (perhaps derived from the game of one-ol'-cat).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Apparently they saw their positions as mutually exclusive.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Some of their points seem more national loyalty than evidence.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Americans tended to reject any suggestion that baseball evolved from an English game, while some English observers concluded that baseball was little more than their rounders without the round.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] One English author went so far as to declare that the Knickerbocker Club comprised English expatriates who introduced "their" game to America for the first time in 1845.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Mills Commission, at the other extreme, created an "official" and entirely fictional All-American version attributing the game's invention to Abner Doubleday in 1839 at Cooperstown, New York (current site of the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Both were entirely wrong, since this much is clear: baseball, or a game called "base ball", had been played in America for many years by then.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A 1791 bylaw in Pittsfield, Massachusetts banned the playing of "any game of wicket, cricket, baseball, batball, football, cats, fives, or any other game played with ball" within 80 yards of the town meeting house to prevent damage to its windows.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Worcester, Massachusetts outlawed playing baseball "in the streets" in 1816.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There are other mentions of baseball during the early 19th century.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The first recorded game of baseball under the later codified rules was played in New York on September 23, 1845, between the New York Baseball Club and the Knickerbocker Baseball Club.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] American baseball was allegedly played in Beachville, Ontario in 1838.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] However, there is no consensus as to the rules that were used or whether it can be considered the first "baseball" game.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A firsthand account and the rules of the game were recalled by Dr.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Ford, who had witnessed the game as a six-year-old boy, in an 1886 issue of *The Sporting Life* magazine in Denver, Colorado; he described the game in remarkable detail, including the precise distances between the irregular bases and how the ball was constructed.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] However, some historians, such as David Block, have expressed doubts as to the veracity and rather incredible specificity of Ford's memory, and indeed compared it to Abner Graves' very similar yarn about Abner Doubleday.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In that letter, Ford refers to 'old grayhairs' at the time, who had played this game as children, suggesting that the origins of baseball in Canada go back into the 18th century.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] That baseball is based on older English games such as stool-ball, trap-ball and tip-cat with possible influences from cricket is difficult to dispute.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] On the other hand, baseball as played in the New World has many elements that are uniquely American.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The earliest published author to muse on the origin of baseball, John Montgomery Ward, was suspicious of the often-parroted claim that rounders is the direct ancestor of baseball, as both were formalized in the same time period.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] He concluded, with some amount of patriotism, that baseball evolved separately from town-ball (i.e. rounders), out of children's "safe haven" ball games.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Games played with bat-and-ball together may all be distant cousins; the same goes for base-and-ball games.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Bat, base, and ball games for two teams that alternate in and out, such as baseball, cricket, and rounders, are likely to be close cousins.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] They all involve throwing a ball to a batsman who attempts to "bat" it away and run safely to a base, while the opponent tries to put the batter-runner out when liable ("liable [to be put out]" is the baseball term for unsafe).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Certainly, baseball is *related* to cricket and rounders, but exactly how, or how closely, has not been established.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The only certain thing is that cricket is much older than baseball, and that cricket was very popular in colonial America and the early United States, fading only with the explosive popularity of New York baseball after the Civil War.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Baseball owes to cricket some adopted terminology, such as "outs", "innings", "runs" and "umpires".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There was also, "wicket", a countrified form of cricket once very popular in New England, which retained the old-fashioned wide, low two-stump wicket, and in which the large ball was rolled along the ground.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The likelihood is that "base ball" and "rounders" (along with "feeder," "squares" and other names) were regional appellations for the same boys' game played with varying rules in many parts of England from the early 1700s onward.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Along with its relatives stool-ball and the cat games it crossed the ocean with English colonists, and eventually followed its own independent evolutionary path, at the same time that back in England what was now generally called "rounders" was developing separately.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The game of "cat" (or "*cat-ball*") had many variations but usually there was a pitcher, a catcher, a batter and fielders, but there were no sides (and often no bases to run).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Often, as in English tip-cat, there was no pitcher and the "cat" was not a ball but an oblong wooden object, roughly football-shaped, which could be flipped into the air by striking one end, or simply a short stick which could be placed over a hole or stone and similarly flipped up.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In other variants the batter himself tossed the ball into the air with his free hand, as in fungo.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] A feature of some versions of cat that would later become a feature of baseball was that a batter would be out if he swung and missed three times.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Another game that was popular in early America was "one ol' cat", the name of which was possibly originally a contraction of *one hole catapult*.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In one ol' cat, when a batter is put out, the catcher goes to bat, the pitcher catches, a fielder becomes the pitcher, and other fielders move up in rotation.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] One ol' cat was often played when there weren't enough players to choose up sides and play townball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Sometimes running to a base and back was involved.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] "Two ol' cat" was the same game as one ol' cat, except that there were two batters; a diagram preserved in the New York Public Library is labeled "Four Old Cat" and depicts a square field like a baseball diamond and four batters, one at each corner.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There are numerous 18th and early 19th-century references in England and especially America to "bat and ball".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Unfortunately, there is no knowledge and information about the game besides the name, nor whether it was an alternate term for baseball or something else such as trap-ball, cat or even cricket.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] It might merely be a generic phrase for any game played with bat and ball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] This "bat and ball," at least, appears very clearly to be a form of early baseball/roundball/townball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Baseball, as it was before the rise to dominance of its altered New York variant in the 1850s and 60s, was known variously as base ball, town ball, round ball, round town, goal ball, field-base, three-corner cat, the New England game, or Massachusetts baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Generally speaking, "round-ball" was the most usual name in New England, "base-ball" in New York, and "town-ball" in Pennsylvania and the South.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The same sheet of paper shows a diagram of a square – 60 feet per side with the base side having in its middle the "Home Goal", "Catcher", and "Striker", and with the corners marked as "1st Goal", "2nd Goal", "3rd Goal", and "4th Goal" as you travel counter-clockwise around the square.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The note accompanying this diagram says, "Thirty or more players (15 or more on each side) with a bat and ball playing Town Ball, some times called Round Ball, and subsequently the so-called Massachusetts game of Base Ball".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Early baseball or town-ball had many, many variants, as would be expected of an informal boys' game, and most differed in several particulars from the game which developed in New York in the 1840s.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In 1833 the Olympic Ball Club of Philadelphia was organized, and by 1837 the Gotham Base Ball Club would be formed in Manhattan, which would later split to form the Knickerbocker Club.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] 1835 saw the publication of *Boy's Book of Sports* which, confusingly, has chapters for both "Base ball" and "Base, or Goal-ball", which seem to be little if at all different; both were "all out, all out" townball with soaking and a three-strike rule.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Of more interest is the fact that here appears the earliest use of the terms "innings" and "diamond".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The early 1840s saw the formation of at least three more clubs in Manhattan, the New York, the Eagle and the Magnolia; another in Philadelphia, the Athletic; and even a club in Cincinnati.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The older game was recognized as being very different in character from the new "Knickerbocker" style.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] That same year the rival Athletic Club traveled to Mauch Chunk, Pennsylvania for a challenge match in which they competed against the local club in both town ball (the home team prevailed, 45–43), and "New York" baseball (Athletic won easily, 34–2).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] This game was played by teams of ten to fourteen players with four bases 60 feet apart and no foul territory.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The ball was considerably smaller and lighter than a modern baseball, and runners were still put out by "soaking".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] David Block's father recalled playing a street game in Brooklyn circa 1915 in which a piece of broomstick was catapulted into the air in like manner, to be struck with the rest of the broomstick; Block Sr. and his chums knew the game as "One Ol' Cat".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In the diagram there is a type-over that makes the first letter of the name of the game hard to distinguish.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The caption provided by the NYPL interprets the note as saying Your Old Cat, but it is likely this is actually Four Old Cat.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] It is however possible that the "New York" and "Gotham" clubs were one and the same.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The interrelationships of the clubs named New York, Gotham and Washington are complex and not well understood by sports historians.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The myth that Abner Doubleday invented baseball in 1839 was once widely promoted and widely believed.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] There is no evidence for this claim except for the testimony of one unreliable man decades later, and there is persuasive counter-evidence.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Doubleday himself never made such a claim; he left many letters and papers, but they contain no description of baseball or any suggestion that he considered himself prominent in the game's history.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] His *New York Times* obituary makes no mention of baseball, nor does a 1911 Encyclopædia article about Doubleday.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The story was attacked by baseball writers almost as soon as it came out, but it had the weight of Major League Baseball and the Spalding publishing empire behind it.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Contrary to popular belief, Doubleday was never inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame, although a large oil portrait of him was on display at the Hall of Fame building for many years.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Doubleday's invention of baseball was the finding of a panel appointed by Albert Spalding, a former star pitcher and club executive, who had become the leading American sporting goods entrepreneur and sports publisher.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Debate on baseball's origins had raged for decades, heating up in the first years of the 20th century, due in part to a 1903 essay baseball historian Henry Chadwick wrote in Spalding's *Official Baseball Guide* stating that baseball gradually evolved from English game of “rounders”.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] To end argument, speculation, and innuendo, Spalding organized the Mills Commission in 1905.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The members were baseball figures, not historians: Spalding's friend Abraham G.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The final report, published on December 30, 1907, included three sections: a summary of the panel's findings written by Mills, a letter by John Montgomery Ward supporting the panel, and a dissenting opinion by Henry Chadwick.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The research methods were, at best, dubious.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Mills was a close friend of Doubleday, and upon Doubleday's death in 1893 Mills orchestrated his memorial service and burial.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Doubleday had been a prominent member of the spiritualist Theosophical Society, in which Spalding's wife was deeply involved and in whose compound in San Diego Spalding was residing at the time.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Wright and Reach were effectively Spalding's employees, as he had secretly bought out their sporting-goods businesses some years before.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] AAU president and Commission secretary Sullivan was Spalding's personal factotum.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Several other members had personal reasons to declare baseball as an "American" game, such as Spalding's strong American imperialist views.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Commission found an appealing story: baseball was invented in a quaint rural town without foreigners or industry, by a young man who later graduated from West Point and served heroically in the Mexican–American War, Civil War, and U.S. wars against Indians.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The Mills Commission concluded that Doubleday had invented baseball in Cooperstown, New York in 1839; that Doubleday had invented the word "baseball", designed the diamond, indicated fielders' positions, and written the rules.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] No written records in the decade between 1839 and 1849 have ever been found to corroborate these claims, nor could Doubleday be interviewed (he died in 1893).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] The principal source for the story was one letter from elderly Abner Graves, who was a five-year-old resident of Cooperstown in 1839.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Graves never mentioned a diamond, positions or the writing of rules.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] What's more, his reliability as a witness was challenged because he spent his final days in an asylum for the criminally insane.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Doubleday was not in Cooperstown in 1839 and may never have visited the town.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] He was enrolled at West Point at the time, and there is no record of any leave time.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Mills, a lifelong friend of Doubleday, never heard him mention baseball, nor is there any mention of the game in Doubleday's autobiography.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] In character, Doubleday was bookish and sedentary, with no observable interest in athletics of any sort.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Versions of baseball rules and descriptions of similar games have been found in publications that significantly predate his alleged invention in 1839.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] Despite this, the ballpark built in 1939 only a few blocks down from the Hall of Fame still bears the name "Doubleday Field".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p01] But this development happened in urban New York City, not pastoral Cooperstown, and the men involved were neither farm boys nor West Point cadets.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The earliest known published rules of baseball in the United States were written in 1845 for a New York City "base ball" club called the Knickerbockers.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The purported organizer of the club, Alexander Cartwright, is one person commonly known as "the father of baseball".
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The rules themselves were written by the two-man Committee on By-Laws, Vice-president William R.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] One important rule, the 13th, outlawed "soaking" or "plugging", putting a runner out by hitting him with a thrown ball, introducing instead the concept of the tag; this reflected the use of a farther-traveling and potentially injurious hard ball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The Knickerbockers also enlarged the diamond well beyond that of town ball, *possibly* to modern size depending on how "paces" is interpreted.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Evolution from the so-called "Knickerbocker Rules" to the current rules is fairly well documented.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] It is noteworthy, however, that the Knickerbocker Rules did not cover a number of basic elements of the game.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] For example, there was no mention of positions or the number of players on a side, the pitching distance was unspecified, the direction of base-running was left open, and it was never stated, though implied, that an "ace" was scored by crossing home plate.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] On June 3, 1953, Congress officially credited Cartwright with inventing the modern game of baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] He was already a member of the Baseball Hall of Fame, having been inducted in 1938 for various other contributions to baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] However, the role of Cartwright himself in the game's invention has been disputed.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] According to Major League Baseball's official historian, John Thorn, "Cartwright's plaque in the Baseball Hall of Fame declares he set the bases 90 feet apart and established nine innings as a game and nine players as a team.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] He did none of these things, and every other word of substance on his plaque is false." His authorship may have been exaggerated in a modern attempt to identify a single inventor of the game, and heavily advanced by a relentless public-relations campaign by his grandson.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The 1845 Rules themselves are signed by the "Committee on By-Laws", William R.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] There is evidence that these rules had been experimented with and used by New York ball clubs for some time; Cartwright, in his 1848 capacity as club secretary (and a bookseller), was merely the first to have them printed up.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Further evidence of a more collective model of New York baseball's development, and doubts as to Cartwright's role as "inventor", came with the 2004 discovery of a newspaper interview with William R.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Wheaton, a founding member of the Gotham Baseball Club in 1837 and first vice president of the Knickerbocker Club, and co-author of its rules, eight years later.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] If Wheaton's account, given in 1887, was correct, then most of the innovations credited to Cartwright were, in fact, the work of the Gothams before the Knickerbockers were formed, including a set of written rules.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] John Thorn, MLB's official historian, argued in his book *Baseball in the Garden of Eden* that four members of the Knickerbockers, namely Wheaton, Louis F.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Wadsworth, Daniel "Doc" Adams and William H.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Tucker, have stronger claims than Cartwright as "inventors" of modern baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Legend holds that Cartwright also introduced the game in most of the towns where he stopped on his trek west to California to find gold, a sort of Johnny Appleseed of baseball.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] This story, however, arose from forged entries in Cartwright's diary which were inserted after his death.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] It is however certain that Cartwright, a New York bookseller who later caught gold fever, umpired a game in Hoboken, New Jersey on June 19, 1846.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The game ended, and the Knickerbockers' opponents (the New York nine) won, 23–1.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] This was long believed to be the first recorded U.S. baseball game between organized clubs.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] However, at least three earlier reported games have since been discovered: on October 10, 1845, a game was played between the New York Ball Club and an unnamed club from Brooklyn, at the Union Star Cricket Grounds in Brooklyn; the New Yorks lost, 22 to 1.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The game was reported in the *New York Morning News* and *True Sun*, making it the first ever published baseball result.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The New Yorks and Brooklyns played two more games on October 21 and 24, with the first on the New Yorks' home diamond at Elysian Fields and the rematch at the Star Cricket Grounds again.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] One point undisputed by historians is that the modern professional major leagues that began in the 1870s developed directly from the amateur urban clubs of the 1840s and 1850s, not from the pastures of small towns such as Cooperstown.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] According to Ford's account of the 1838 Beachville game, "I will remember when some fellows down at or near New York got up the game of base ball that ... was played with a ball hard as a stick.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The 4th Rule specified the distance from first to third, and home to second, as being 42 paces.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] If a "pace" is taken to be the same as a yard, three feet, then the distance would have been 126 feet, or 89 feet between bases.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] However, most contemporary sources, such as Noah Webster's dictionary, considered a "pace" to be two and a half feet, meaning the base distance would have been about 75 feet (still larger than townball's typical 40 to 60).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Or were simply variable depending on how many players were available; during their first decade the Knicks played games with as few as seven and as many as thirteen on a side.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The *True Sun* account of the first game read "*The Base Ball match between eight Brooklyn players, and eight players of New York, came off on Friday on the grounds of the Union Star Cricket Club.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The Yorkers were singularly unfortunate in scoring but one run in their three innings.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In 1845, the Knickerbocker Club began using Elysian Fields in Hoboken to play baseball, following the New York and Magnolia Ball Clubs which had begun playing there in 1843.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] On October 21, 1845, the New York Ball Club played the second of their three games against a Brooklyn team there, the series being the first known inter-club baseball games.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In June 1846 the Knickerbockers played the "New York nine" (probably the same New York Ball Club) in the first baseball game played between clubs according to codified rules.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] A plaque and baseball diamond street pavings at 11th and Washington Streets commemorate the event.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] By the 1850s, several Manhattan-based members of the National Association of Base Ball Players were using the grounds as their home field.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In 1865 the grounds hosted a championship match between the Mutual Club of New York and the Atlantic Club of Brooklyn that was attended by an estimated 20,000 fans and captured in the Currier & Ives lithograph *The American National Game of Base Ball*.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] With the construction of two significant baseball parks enclosed by fences in Brooklyn, enabling promoters there to charge admission to games; the prominence of Elysian Fields began to diminish.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In 1868 the leading Manhattan club, Mutual, shifted its home games to the Union Grounds in Brooklyn.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In 1880, the founders of the professional National League's New York club and the Metropolitan Club of the American Association finally succeeded in siting a ballpark in Manhattan at the former Polo Grounds on 110th Street.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The Knickerbockers published their rulebook in 1848, including one significant change: the introduction of the force-out, but only at first base.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In 1852, the Eagle Club published their rules, and two years later the Knickerbockers, Eagles and Gothams met and agreed to a uniform set of rules to govern all three clubs, at least in match play, which for the first time set the pitching distance (15 paces).
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] A preliminary meeting in 1855 between seven other clubs, five from New York and one each from Brooklyn and New Jersey, represented the first effort to form an organized league, although it came to nothing.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The convention also defined the distance between the bases unambiguously as 90 feet, and specified nine-man teams.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The following year, twenty-five clubs including one from New Jersey established an ongoing governing body with officers, constitution and by-laws, but the National Association of Base Ball Players is conventionally dated from the first meeting in 1857.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] It governed through 1870 but it scheduled and sanctioned no games.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In 1858, clubs from the association played a cross-town, all-star series pitting Brooklyn clubs against clubs from New York and Hoboken.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] On July 20, 1858, an estimated crowd of about 4,000 spectators watched New York and Hoboken defeat Brooklyn by a score of 22–18.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The New York team included players from the Union, Empire, Eagle, Knickerbocker and Gotham clubs.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The Brooklyn team included players from the clubs Excelsior, Eckford, Atlantic and Putnam.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] This was the first baseball game played before a paying crowd, with tickets priced at ten cents; the surplus receipts after costs were donated to charity.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] In a return match held August 17, 1858, and played at the Fashion Course in the Corona neighborhood of Queens, a slightly smaller crowd cheered Brooklyn to a win over New York and Hoboken by a score of 29–8.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] New York won a third game in the series, also played at the Fashion Course, on September 10, 1858.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] By 1862 some NABBP member clubs offered games to the general public in enclosed ballparks with admission fees.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] During and after the American Civil War (1861–1865), the movements of soldiers and exchanges of prisoners helped spread the game.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] As of the December 1865 meeting, the year the war ended, there were isolated Association clubs in Fort Leavenworth, St.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Louis, Louisville, and Chattanooga, Tennessee, along with about 90 member clubs north and east of Washington, D.C.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] All of these clubs were nominally amateur, although by the late 1860s the strongest clubs' best players were being paid under the table.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] For the 1869 season the NABBP, in an effort to take the corrupting money out of the amateur game, permitted the formation of professional teams.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] This move, however, backfired, as the pro game exploded in popularity and amateur club baseball quickly died out.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] By far the most successful of the new professional clubs, the Cincinnati Red Stockings, recruited nationally and effectively toured nationally, and no one beat them until June 1870.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Their success led to the founding of the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players in 1871 and its successor, the National League of Professional Base Ball Clubs in 1876, the elder of baseball's two Major Leagues and the oldest professional sports league in the world.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Already in the 19th century, the "old game" was invoked for special exhibitions such as reunions and anniversaries – and for making moral points.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Today hundreds of clubs in the U.S. play "vintage base ball" according to the 1845, 1858, or later rules (up to about 1887), usually in vintage uniforms.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Some of them have supporting casts that recreate period dress and manner, especially those associated with living history museums.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] The origins of baseball were summarized in a documentary produced by Major League Baseball in 2009 titled *Base Ball Discovered*.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Plus an additional twenty or thirty cents for parking one-horse or two-horse vehicles, respectively.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] Expensive parking is an old baseball tradition.
[src:baseball-almanac/baseball-history-p02] England's Football Association was organized in 1863, but was amateur until 1885.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Although originally established to educate Native Americans in Christian theology and the Anglo-American way of life, the university primarily trained Congregationalist ministers during its early history before it gradually secularized.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] While Dartmouth is now a research university rather than simply an undergraduate college, it focuses on undergraduate education and continues to go by "Dartmouth College" to emphasize this.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In addition to the undergraduate faculty of arts and sciences, Dartmouth has four professional and graduate schools: the Geisel School of Medicine, the Thayer School of Engineering, the Tuck School of Business, and the Guarini School of Graduate and Advanced Studies.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The university also has affiliations with the Dartmouth–Hitchcock Medical Center.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is home to the Rockefeller Center for Public Policy and the Social Sciences, the Hood Museum of Art, the John Sloan Dickey Center for International Understanding, and the Hopkins Center for the Arts.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] With a student enrollment of about 6,700, Dartmouth is the smallest university in the Ivy League.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Undergraduate admissions are highly selective with an acceptance rate of 5.3% for the class of 2028, including a 3.8% rate for regular decision applicants.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Situated on a terrace above the Connecticut River, Dartmouth's 269-acre (109 ha) main campus is in the rural Upper Valley region of New England.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The university functions on a quarter system, operating year-round on four ten-week academic terms.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is known for its undergraduate focus, Greek culture, and campus traditions.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Its 34 varsity sports teams compete intercollegiately in the Ivy League conference of the NCAA Division I.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The university has many prominent alumni, including 170 members of the United States Congress, 25 U.S. governors, 8 U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Cabinet secretaries, 3 Nobel Prize laureates, 2 U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Supreme Court justices, and a U.S. vice president.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Other notable alumni include 83 Rhodes Scholars, 26 Marshall Scholarship recipients, 13 Pulitzer Prize recipients, 10 current CEOs of *Fortune* 500 companies, and 51 Olympic medalists.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth was founded by Eleazar Wheelock, a Yale graduate and Congregational minister from Windham, Connecticut, who had sought to establish a school to train Native Americans as Christian missionaries.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] It was one of the nine colonial colleges chartered before the American Revolution.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Wheelock's ostensible inspiration for such an establishment resulted from his relationship with Mohegan Indian Samson Occom.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Occom became an ordained minister after studying under Wheelock from 1743 to 1747, and later moved to Long Island to preach to the Montauks.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Wheelock founded Moor's Indian Charity School in 1755.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Charity School proved somewhat successful, but additional funding was necessary to continue school's operations, and Wheelock sought the help of friends to raise money.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The first major donation to the school was given by John Phillips in 1762, who went on to found Phillips Exeter Academy.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Occom, accompanied by the Reverend Nathaniel Whitaker, traveled to England in 1766 to raise money from churches.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] With these funds, they established a trust to help Wheelock.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The head of the trust was a Methodist named William Legge, 2nd Earl of Dartmouth.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Although the fund provided Wheelock ample financial support for the Charity School, Wheelock initially had trouble recruiting Indians to the institution, primarily because its location was far from tribal territories.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In seeking to expand the school into a college, Wheelock relocated it to Hanover, in the Province of New Hampshire.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The move from Connecticut followed a lengthy and sometimes frustrating effort to find resources and secure a charter.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Royal Governor of New Hampshire, John Wentworth, provided the land upon which Dartmouth would be built and on December 13, 1769, issued a royal charter in the name of King George III establishing the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The reference to educating Native American youth was included to connect Dartmouth to the Charity School and enable the use of the Charity School's unspent trust funds.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college granted its first degrees in 1771.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Given the limited success of the Charity School, however, Wheelock intended his new college as one primarily for whites.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Occom, disappointed with Wheelock's departure from the school's original goal of Indian Christianization, went on to form his own community of New England Indians called Brothertown Indians in New York.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1819, Dartmouth College was the subject of the historic Dartmouth College case, which challenged New Hampshire's 1816 attempt to amend the college charter to make the school a public university.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] An institution called Dartmouth University occupied the college buildings and began operating in Hanover in 1817, though the college continued teaching classes in rented rooms nearby.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Daniel Webster, an alumnus of the class of 1801, presented the college's case to the Supreme Court, which found the amendment of Dartmouth's charter to be an illegal impairment of a contract by the state and reversed New Hampshire's takeover of the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Webster concluded his peroration with the famous words: "It is, Sir, as I have said, a small college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth taught its first African-American students in 1775 and 1808.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] By the end of the Civil War, 20 black men had attended the college or its medical school, and Dartmouth "was recognized in the African-American community as a place where a man of color could go to get educated".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] One of those first 20 black alumni, Jonathan C.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Gibbs, served as Secretary of State and Superintendent of Public Instruction for the state of Florida.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1866, the New Hampshire College of Agriculture and the Mechanic Arts was incorporated in Hanover, in connection with Dartmouth College.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The institution was officially associated with Dartmouth and was directed by Dartmouth's president.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The new college was moved to Durham, New Hampshire, in 1891, and later became known as the University of New Hampshire.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth emerged onto the national academic stage at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Prior to this period, the college had clung to traditional methods of instruction and was relatively poorly funded.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Under President William Jewett Tucker (1893–1909), Dartmouth underwent a major revitalization of facilities, faculty, and the student body, following large endowments such as the $10,000 given by Dartmouth alumnus and law professor John Ordronaux.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] 20 new structures replaced antiquated buildings, while the student body and faculty both expanded threefold.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Tucker is often credited for having "refounded Dartmouth" and bringing it into national prestige.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Presidents Ernest Fox Nichols (1909–16) and Ernest Martin Hopkins (1916–45) continued Tucker's trend of modernization, further improving campus facilities and introducing selective admissions in the 1920s.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1945, Hopkins was subject to no small amount of controversy, as he openly admitted to Dartmouth's practice of using racial quotas to deny Jews entry into the university.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] John Sloan Dickey, serving as president from 1945 until 1970, strongly emphasized the liberal arts, particularly public policy and international relations.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] During World War II, Dartmouth was one of 131 colleges and universities nationally that took part in the V-12 Navy College Training Program which offered students a path to a navy commission.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Dartmouth workshop, which was held in 1956, is widely considered to be the founding event of artificial intelligence as a field.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1970, longtime professor of mathematics and computer science John George Kemeny became president of Dartmouth.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Kemeny oversaw several major changes at the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth, which had been a men's institution, began admitting women as full-time students and undergraduate degree candidates in 1972 amid much controversy.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] At about the same time, the college adopted its "Dartmouth Plan" of academic scheduling, permitting the student body to increase in size within the existing facilities.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1988, Dartmouth's alma mater song's lyrics changed from "Men of Dartmouth" to "Dear old Dartmouth".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] During the 1990s, the college saw a major academic overhaul under President James O.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Freedman and a controversial (and ultimately unsuccessful) 1999 initiative to encourage the school's single-sex Greek houses to go coed.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The first decade of the 21st century saw the commencement of the $1.5 billion Campaign for the Dartmouth Experience, the largest capital fundraising campaign in the college's history, which surpassed $1 billion in 2008.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The mid- and late first decade of the 21st century have also seen extensive campus construction, with the erection of two new housing complexes, full renovation of two dormitories, and a forthcoming dining hall, life sciences center, and visual arts center.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2004, Booz Allen Hamilton selected Dartmouth College as a model of institutional endurance "whose record of endurance has had implications and benefits for all American organizations, both academic and commercial", citing *Dartmouth College v.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Woodward* and Dartmouth's successful self-reinvention in the late 19th century.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Since the election of a number of petition-nominated trustees to the Board of Trustees starting in 2004, the role of alumni in Dartmouth governance has been the subject of ongoing conflict.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] President James Wright announced his retirement in February 2008 and was replaced by Harvard University professor and physician Jim Yong Kim on July 1, 2009.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In early August 2019, Dartmouth College agreed to pay nine current and former students a total of $14 million to settle a class-action lawsuit alleging they were sexually harassed by three former neuroscience professors.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In April 2022, Dartmouth College returned the papers of Samson Occom, who helped Eleazar Wheelock secure the funds for Dartmouth College for what Occom believed would be a school for Native students in Connecticut, to the Mohegan Tribe.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] On June 12, 2023 Sian Beilock began her tenure as the first female president of Dartmouth.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In September 2023, Dartmouth convened an event entitled The Future of Mental Health and Wellness, which included the seven living U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2024, the college hired a chief wellness office in order to provide increased mental health support on campus and to help students to manage daily stressors.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In April 2024, Dartmouth announced the creation of the Dartmouth Climate Collaboration, pledging $500 million towards the goal of eliminating carbon emissions on campus by 2050.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The plan includes the installation of high-capacity heat pumps and a geoexchange system, making it the largest operational change in the college's history.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth, a liberal arts institution, offers a four-year Bachelor of Arts and an ABET-accredited Bachelor of Engineering degree to undergraduate students.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college has 39 academic departments offering 56 major programs, while students are free to design special majors or engage in dual majors.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] For the graduating class of 2017, the most popular majors were economics, government, computer science, engineering sciences, and history.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Economics Department, whose prominent professors include David Blanchflower, Andrew Samwick, and Diego Comin, among others, also holds the distinction as the top-ranked bachelor's-only economics program in the world.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Government Department similarly includes numerous eminent faculty members, such as Stephen Brooks and William Wohlforth, and is among Dartmouth's most popular majors.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] These two departments are known for enforcing a median grade of B+ in most of their courses in order to curb the burgeoning trend of grade inflation at American universities.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In order to graduate, a student must complete 35 total courses, eight to ten of which are typically part of a chosen major program.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Other requirements for graduation include the completion of ten "distributive requirements" in a variety of academic fields, proficiency in a foreign language, and completion of a writing class and first-year seminar in writing.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Many departments offer honors programs requiring students seeking that distinction to engage in "independent, sustained work", culminating in the production of a thesis.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In addition to the courses offered in Hanover, Dartmouth offers 57 different off-campus programs, including Foreign Study Programs, Language Study Abroad programs, and Exchange Programs.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Through the Graduate Studies program, Dartmouth grants doctorate and master's degrees in 19 Arts & Sciences graduate programs.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Although the first graduate degree, a PhD in classics, was awarded in 1885, many of the current PhD programs have only existed since the 1960s.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Furthermore, Dartmouth is home to three professional schools: the Geisel School of Medicine (established 1797), Thayer School of Engineering (1867)—which also serves as the undergraduate department of engineering sciences—and Tuck School of Business (1900).
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] With these professional schools and graduate programs, conventional American usage would accord Dartmouth the label of "Dartmouth University"; however, because of historical and nostalgic reasons (such as *Dartmouth College v.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Woodward*), the school uses the name "Dartmouth College" to refer to the entire institution.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth employs a total of 607 tenured or tenure-track faculty members, including the highest proportion of female tenured professors among the Ivy League universities, and the first black woman tenure-track faculty member in computer science at an Ivy League university.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth served as the host member of the University Press of New England from its founding in 1970 until its closure in 2018.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth College is a research institution designated by the Carnegie Classification of Institutions of Higher Education as having "very high research activity".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2019, Dartmouth College was elected to the Association of American Universities (AAU), an organization of 69 research universities.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Faculty members have been at the forefront of such major academic developments as the Dartmouth Workshop, the Dartmouth Time-Sharing System, Dartmouth BASIC, and Dartmouth ALGOL 30.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2005, sponsored project awards to Dartmouth faculty research amounted to $169 million.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2017, Eric Fossum, a professor of engineering at Dartmouth College, was awarded the Queen Elizabeth Prize for his work on imaging sensor technology.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Pfizer–BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine, which was approved in 2021, was based on findings that originated in a science lab at the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2024, researchers at Dartmouth received a $31.3 million grant from the federal government to further their study of prostate cancer.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2025, Dartmouth received approximately $97 million worth of funding from the National Institutes of Health.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth was ranked 12th among undergraduate programs at national universities by *U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] News & World Report* in its 2022 rankings.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] News* also ranked the school 3rd best for veterans, tied for 5th best in undergraduate teaching, and 7th for "best value" national universities.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's undergraduate teaching was previously ranked 1st by *U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth College is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In *Forbes*' 2019 rankings of 650 universities, liberal arts colleges and service academies, Dartmouth ranked 10th overall and 10th in research universities.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In the *Forbes* 2018 "grateful graduate" rankings, Dartmouth came in first for the second year in a row.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The 2021*Academic Ranking of World Universities* ranked Dartmouth among the 90–110th best universities in the nation.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Undergraduate admission to Dartmouth College is characterized by the Carnegie Foundation and *U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] News & World Report* as "most selective".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The *Princeton Review*, in its 2024 edition, gave the university an admissions selectivity rating of 99 out of 99.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] For the freshman class entering Fall 2023, Dartmouth received a record 28,841 applications of which 6.2% were accepted, consistent with the prior two years; approximately 67% of those accepted are expected to matriculate.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Of those admitted students who reported class rank, 444 were ranked first or second in their class, while 96% ranked in the top decile.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The admitted students' academic profile showed an all-time high SAT average score of 1501, while the average composite ACT score remained at 33.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Additionally, for the 2016–2017 academic year, Dartmouth received 685 transfer applications of which 5.1% were accepted, with an average SAT composite score of 1490, average composite ACT score of 34, and average college GPA of about 3.85.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth meets 100% of students' demonstrated financial need in order to attend the college, and currently admits all students, including internationals, on a need-blind basis.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2020, Dartmouth made it optional for students applying to the college to submit their SAT scores due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2024, the college became the first Ivy League school to announce that it would once again require applicants to submit their test scores.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth guarantees to meet 100% of the demonstrated need of every admitted student who applies for financial aid at the time of admission.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is one of seven American universities to practice international need-blind admissions.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] This means that all applicants, including U.S. permanent residents, undocumented students in the U.S., and international students, are admitted to the college without regard to their financial circumstances.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] At Dartmouth, free tuition is provided for students from families with total incomes of $125,000 or less and possessing typical assets.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is also one of a few U.S. universities to eliminate undergraduate student loans and replace them with expanded scholarship grants.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2015, $88.8 million (~$114 million in 2024) in need-based scholarships were awarded to Dartmouth students.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The median family income of Dartmouth students is $200,400, with 58% of students coming from the top 10% highest-earning families and 14% from the bottom 60%.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In March 2024, the estate of Glenn Britt gifted over $150 million to Dartmouth to enable students from middle-income families to attend the college for free.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth functions on a quarter system, operating year-round on four ten-week academic terms.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Dartmouth Plan (or simply "D-Plan") is an academic scheduling system that permits the customization of each student's academic year.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] All undergraduates are required to be in residence for the fall, winter, and spring terms of their freshman year and two terms of their senior year, as well as the summer term of their sophomore year.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] However, students may petition to alter this plan so that they may be off during terms of their senior year or sophomore summer terms.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] During all terms, students are permitted to choose between studying on-campus, studying at an off-campus program, or taking a term off for vacation, outside internships, or research projects.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The typical course load is three classes per term, and students will generally enroll in classes for 12 total terms over the course of their academic career.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The D-Plan was instituted in the early 1970s at the same time that Dartmouth began accepting female undergraduates.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] It was initially devised as a plan to increase the enrollment without enlarging campus accommodations, and has been described as "a way to put 4,000 students into 3,000 beds".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Although new dormitories have been built since, the number of students has also increased and the D-Plan remains in effect.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] It was modified in the 1980s in an attempt to reduce the problems of lack of social and academic continuity.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is governed by a board of trustees comprising the college president (*ex officio*), the state governor (*ex officio*), 13 trustees nominated and elected by the board (called "charter trustees"), and eight trustees nominated by alumni and elected by the board ("alumni trustees").
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The nominees for alumni trustee are determined by a poll of the members of the Association of Alumni of Dartmouth College, selecting from among names put forward by the Alumni Council or by alumni petition.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Although the board elected its members from the two sources of nominees in equal proportions between 1891 and 2007, the board decided in 2007 to add several new members, all charter trustees.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In the controversy that followed the decision, the Association of Alumni filed a lawsuit, although it later withdrew the action.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2008, the board added five new charter trustees.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college is an active member of the University of the Arctic.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] UArctic is an international cooperative network based in the Circumpolar Arctic region, consisting of more than 200 universities, colleges, and other organizations with an interest in promoting education and research in the Arctic region.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth College is situated in the rural town of Hanover, New Hampshire, located in the Upper Valley along the Connecticut River in New England.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Its 269-acre (1.09 km2) campus is centered on a 5-acre (2 ha) "Green", a former field of pine trees cleared in 1771.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is the largest private landowner of the town of Hanover, and its total landholdings and facilities are worth an estimated $434 million.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In addition to its campus in Hanover, Dartmouth owns 4,500 acres (18 km2) of Mount Moosilauke in the White Mountains and a 27,000-acre (110 km2) tract of land in northern New Hampshire known as the Second College Grant.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's campus buildings vary in age from Wentworth and Thornton Halls of the 1820s (the oldest surviving buildings constructed by the college) to new dormitories and mathematics facilities completed in 2006.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Most of Dartmouth's buildings are designed in the Georgian colonial architecture style, a theme which has been preserved in recent architectural additions.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college has actively sought to reduce carbon emissions and energy usage on campus, earning it the grade of A− from the Sustainable Endowments Institute on its College Sustainability Report Card 2008.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] A notable feature of the Dartmouth campus is its many trees which (despite Dutch elm disease) include some 200 American elms.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The campus also has the largest Kentucky coffeetree in New Hampshire, at 91 ft tall.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] While Dartmouth's campus is located in a rural setting, it is connected to several major cities by intercity bus services that directly serve Dartmouth and Hanover.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth Coach provides service from Hanover to South Station and Logan International Airport in Boston as well as New York City, while Greyhound Lines operates a daily route connecting Hanover and Montreal.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] All three cities are popular weekend/vacation destinations for Dartmouth students.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college's creative and performing arts facility is the Hopkins Center for the Arts ("the Hop").
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Opened in 1962, the Hop houses the college's drama, music, film, and studio arts departments, as well as a woodshop, pottery studio, and jewelry studio which are open for use by students and faculty.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The building was designed by the famed architect Wallace Harrison, who would later design the similar-looking façade of Manhattan's Metropolitan Opera House at Lincoln Center.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Its facilities include two theaters and one 900-seat auditorium and the Courtyard Café dining facility.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Hop is connected to the Hood Museum of Art, arguably North America's oldest museum in continuous operation, and the Loew Auditorium, where films are screened.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In addition to its 19 graduate programs in the arts and sciences, Dartmouth is home to three separate graduate schools.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Geisel School of Medicine is located in a complex on the north side of campus and includes laboratories, classrooms, offices, and a biomedical library.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Dartmouth–Hitchcock Medical Center, located several miles to the south in Lebanon, New Hampshire, contains a 396-bed teaching hospital for the Medical School.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Thayer School of Engineering and the Tuck School of Business are both located at the end of Tuck Mall, west of the center of campus and near the Connecticut River.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Thayer School comprises two buildings; Tuck has seven academic and administrative buildings, as well as several common areas.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The two graduate schools share a library, the Feldberg Business & Engineering Library.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In December 2018, Dartmouth began a major expansion of the west end of campus by breaking ground on the $200 million (~$245 million in 2024) Center for Engineering and Computer Science.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The center will house the Computer Science department and Magnuson Center for Entrepreneurship.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In October 2019, construction began on the Irving Institute of Energy and Society.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Both were completed by Spring 2022, and the Center for Engineering and Computer Science was renamed the Class of 1982 Engineering and Computer Science Center.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's libraries are all part of the collective Dartmouth College Library, which comprises 2.48 million volumes and 6 million total resources, including videos, maps, sound recordings, and photographs.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Its specialized libraries include the Biomedical Libraries, Evans Map Room, Feldberg Business & Engineering Library, Jones Media Center, Rauner Special Collections Library, and Sherman Art Library.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Baker-Berry Library is the main library at Dartmouth, consisting of a merger of the Baker Memorial Library (opened 1928) and the Berry Library (completed 2002).
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Located on the northern side of the Green, Baker's 200-foot (61 m) tower is an iconic symbol of the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's original sports field was the Green, where students played cricket and old division football during the 19th century.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Today, two of Dartmouth's athletic facilities are located in the southeast corner of campus.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The center of athletic life is the Alumni Gymnasium, which includes the Karl Michael Competition Pool and the Spaulding Pool, a fitness center, a weight room, and a 1/13th-mile (123 m) indoor track.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Attached to Alumni Gymnasium is the Berry Sports Center, which contains basketball and volleyball courts (Leede Arena), as well as the Kresge Fitness Center.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Behind the Alumni Gymnasium is Memorial Field, a 15,600-seat stadium overlooking Dartmouth's football field and track.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The nearby Thompson Arena, designed by Italian engineer Pier Luigi Nervi and constructed in 1975, houses Dartmouth's ice rink.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Also visible from Memorial Field is the 91,800-square-foot (8,530 m2) Nathaniel Leverone Fieldhouse, home to the indoor track.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The new softball field, Dartmouth Softball Park, was constructed in 2012, sharing parking facilities with Thompson arena and replacing Sachem Field, located over a mile from campus, as the primary softball facility.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's close association and involvement in the development of the downhill skiing industry is featured in the 2010 book *Passion for Skiing* as well as the 2013 documentary based on the book *Passion for Snow*.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth used to have nine residential communities located throughout campus, instead of ungrouped dormitories or residential colleges.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The dormitories varied in design from modern to traditional Georgian styles, and room arrangements range from singles to quads and apartment suites.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Since 2006, the college has guaranteed housing for students during their freshman and sophomore years.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] More than 3,000 students elect to live in housing provided by college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In November 2022, Dartmouth Hall was rededicated after a $42 million renovation.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Fundraising for the project was led by over 1700 alumnae as part of the celebration of 50 years of coeducation at Dartmouth College.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Campus meals are served by Dartmouth Dining Services, which operates 11 dining establishments around campus.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Class of 1953 Commons, commonly referred to as "Foco", is the all-you-can-eat dining hall, located at the center of campus.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Collis Center is the center of student life and programming, serving as what would be generically termed the "student union" or "campus center".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] It contains a café, study space, common areas, and a number of administrative departments, including the Academic Skills Center.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Robinson Hall, next door to both the Collis Center and the Class of 1953 Commons, contains the offices of a number of student organizations, including the Dartmouth Outing Club and *The Dartmouth* daily newspaper.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth Student Government represents students on issues related to student life.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Annually, students elect a student body president, vice president, and undergraduate senate to represent them in the following academic year.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2006, *The Princeton Review* ranked Dartmouth third in its "Quality of Life" category, and sixth for having the "Happiest Students".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Athletics and participation in the Greek system are the most popular campus activities.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In all, Dartmouth offers more than 350 organizations, teams, and sports.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The school is also home to a variety of longstanding traditions and celebrations and has a loyal alumni network; Dartmouth ranked #2 in "The Princeton Review" in 2006 for Best Alumni Network.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2014, Dartmouth College was the third highest in the nation in "total of reports of rape" on their main campus, with 42 reports of rape.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] *The Washington Post* attributed the high number of rape reports to the fact that a growing number of sexual assault victims feel comfortable enough to report sexual assaults that would have gone unreported in previous years.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth fraternities have an extensive history of hazing and alcohol abuse, leading to police raids and accusations of sexual harassment.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's more than 200 student organizations and clubs cover a wide range of interests.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2007, the college hosted eight academic groups, 17 cultural groups, two honor societies, 30 "issue-oriented" groups, 25 performing groups, 12 pre-professional groups, 20 publications, and 11 recreational groups.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] *The Dartmouth* describes itself as "America's Oldest College Newspaper, Founded 1799".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Partially because of Dartmouth's rural, isolated location, the Greek system dating from the 1840s is one of the most popular social outlets for students.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is home to 32 recognized Greek houses: 17 fraternities, 12 sororities, and three coeducational organizations.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2007, roughly 70% of eligible students belonged to a Greek organization; since 1987, students have not been permitted to join Greek organizations until their sophomore year.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth College was among the first institutions of higher education to desegregate fraternity houses, doing so in the 1950s, and was involved in the movement to create coeducational Greek houses in the 1970s.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In the early first decade of the 21st century, campus-wide debate focused on a board of trustees recommendation that Greek organizations become "substantially coeducational"; this attempt to change the Greek system eventually failed.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth also has a number of secret societies, which are student- and alumni-led organizations often focused on preserving the history of the college and initiating service projects.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Most prominent among them is the Sphinx society, housed in a prominent Egyptian tomb-like building near the center of campus.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Sphinx has been the subject of numerous rumors as to its facilities, practices, and membership.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college has an additional classification of social/residential organizations known as undergraduate societies.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Approximately 20% of students participate in a varsity sport, and nearly 80% participate in some form of club, varsity, intramural, or other athletics.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2021, Dartmouth College fielded 33 intercollegiate varsity teams: 15 for men, 17 for women, and coeducational sailing and equestrian programs.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's athletic teams compete in the NCAA Division I eight-member Ivy League conference; some teams also participate in the Eastern College Athletic Conference (ECAC).
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] As is mandatory for the members of the Ivy League, Dartmouth College does not offer athletic scholarships.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In addition to the traditional American team sports (football, basketball, baseball, and ice hockey), Dartmouth competes at the varsity level in many other sports including track and field, softball, squash, sailing, tennis, rowing, soccer, skiing, and lacrosse.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college also offers 26 club and intramural sports such as fencing, rugby, water polo, figure skating, boxing, volleyball, ultimate frisbee, and cricket, leading to a 75% participation rate in athletics among the undergraduate student body.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Dartmouth Fencing Team, despite being entirely self-coached, won the USACFC club national championship in 2014.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Dartmouth Men's Rugby Team, founded in 1951, has been ranked among the best collegiate teams in that sport, winning for example the Ivy Rugby Conference every year between 2008 and 2020.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The figure skating team won the national championship five straight times from 2004 through 2008.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In addition to the academic requirements for graduation, Dartmouth requires every undergraduate to complete a 50-yard (46 m) swim and three terms of physical education.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] However, Wheelock primarily intended the college to educate white youth, and the few Native students that attended Dartmouth experienced much difficulty in an institution ostensibly dedicated to their education.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The funds for the Charity School for Native Americans that preceded Dartmouth College were raised primarily by the efforts of a Mohegan named Samson Occom, and at least some of those funds were used to help found the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college graduated only 19 Native Americans during its first 200 years.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1970, the college established Native American academic and social programs as part of a "new dedication to increasing Native American enrollment".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Since then, Dartmouth has graduated over 700 Native American students from over 200 different tribes, more than the other seven Ivy League universities combined.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth is well known for its fierce school spirit and many traditions.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The college functions on a quarter system, and one weekend each term is set aside as a traditional celebratory event, known on campus as "big weekends" or "party weekends".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In the fall term, Homecoming (officially called Dartmouth Night) is marked by a bonfire on the Green constructed by the freshman class.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Winter term is celebrated by Winter Carnival, a tradition started in 1911 by the Dartmouth Outing Club to promote winter sports.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] This tradition is the oldest in the United States, and subsequently went on to catch on at other New England colleges.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In the spring, Green Key is a weekend mostly devoted to campus parties and celebration.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The summer term was formerly marked by Tubestock, an unofficial tradition in which the students used wooden rafts and inner tubes to float on the Connecticut River.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Begun in 1986, Tubestock was ended in 2006 by town ordinance.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Class of 2008, during their summer term on campus in 2006, replaced the defunct Tubestock with Fieldstock.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] This new celebration includes a barbecue, live music, and the revival of the 1970s and 1980s tradition of racing homemade chariots around the Green.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Unlike Tubestock, Fieldstock is funded and supported by the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Another longstanding tradition is four-day, student-run First-Year Trips for incoming freshmen, begun in 1935.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Each trip concludes at the Moosilauke Ravine Lodge.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 2011, over 96% of freshmen elected to participate.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's motto, chosen by Eleazar Wheelock, is *Vox clamantis in deserto*.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The Latin motto is literally translated as "The voice of one crying in the wilderness", but is more often rendered as "A voice crying out in the wilderness".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The phrase appears five times in the Bible and is a reference to the college's location on what was once the frontier of European settlement.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Richard Hovey's "Men of Dartmouth" was elected as the best of Dartmouth's songs in 1896, and became the school's official song in 1926.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The song was retitled to "Alma Mater" in the 1980s when its lyrics were changed to refer to women as well as men.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth's 1769 royal charter required the creation of a seal for use on official documents and diplomas.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Engraved by a Boston silversmith, the seal was ready by commencement of 1773.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] On October 28, 1926, the trustees affirmed the charter's reservation of the seal for official corporate documents alone.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The College Publications Committee commissioned noted typographer William Addison Dwiggins to create a line drawing version of the seal in 1940 that saw widespread use.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dwiggins' design was modified during 1957 to change the date from "1770" to "1769", to accord with the date of the college charter.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The trustees commissioned a new set of dies with a date of "1769" to replace the old dies, now badly worn after almost two hundred years of use.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] On October 28, 1926, the trustees approved a "Dartmouth College Shield" for general use.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Parke Johnson designed this emblem on the basis of the shield that is depicted at the center of the original seal.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] On June 9, 1944, the trustees approved another coat of arms based on the shield part of the seal, this one by Canadian artist and designer Thoreau MacDonald.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] That design was used widely and, like Dwiggins' seal, had its date changed from "1770" to "1769" around 1958.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] That version continues to be used under trademark registration number 3112676 and others.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] College designer John Scotford made a stylized version of the shield during the 1960s, but it did not see the success of MacDonald's design.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The shield appears to have been used as the basis of the shield of the Geisel School of Medicine, and it has been reproduced in sizes as small as 20 micrometers across.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The design has appeared on Rudolph Ruzicka's Bicentennial Medal (Philadelphia Mint, 1969) and elsewhere.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Dartmouth has never had an official mascot.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] The nickname "The Big Green", originating in the 1860s, is based on students' adoption of a shade of forest green ("Dartmouth Green") as the school's official color in 1866.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Beginning in the 1920s, the Dartmouth College athletic teams were known by their unofficial nickname "the Indians", a moniker that probably originated among sports journalists.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] This unofficial mascot and team name was used until the early 1970s, when its use came under criticism.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In 1974, the Trustees declared the "use of the [Indian] symbol in any form to be inconsistent with present institutional and academic objectives of the College in advancing Native American education".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Some alumni and students, as well as the conservative student newspaper, *The Dartmouth Review*, have sought to return the Indian symbol to prominence, but never succeeded in doing so.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Various student initiatives have been undertaken to adopt a mascot, but none has become "official".
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] One proposal devised by the college humor magazine the *Dartmouth Jack-O-Lantern* was Keggy the Keg, an anthropomorphic beer keg who makes occasional appearances at college sporting events.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] Despite student enthusiasm for Keggy, the mascot has received approval from only the student government.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p01] In November 2006, student government attempted to revive the "Dartmoose" amid renewed controversy surrounding the former unofficial Indian mascot.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dartmouth's alumni are known for frequently donating to their alma mater.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] By 2008, Dartmouth had graduated 238 classes of students, and had over 60,000 living alumni in a variety of fields.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Finance, consulting, and technology have consistently been the most popular industries to enter for students.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Top employers of new graduates include Goldman Sachs, Morgan Stanley, McKinsey & Company, Bain & Company, Amazon, Microsoft, and Google.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Rockefeller, 41st Vice President of the United States and 49th Governor of New York, graduated cum laude from Dartmouth with a degree in economics in 1930.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Over 164 Dartmouth graduates have served in the United States Senate and United States House of Representatives, such as Massachusetts statesman Daniel Webster.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Cabinet members of American presidents include Attorney General Amos T.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Forrestal, Secretary of Labor Robert Reich, Secretary of the Treasury Henry Paulson, and Secretary of the Treasury Timothy Geithner.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Everett Koop was the Surgeon General of the United States under President Ronald Reagan.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Two Dartmouth alumni have served as justices on the Supreme Court of the United States: Salmon P.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Eugene Norman Veasey (class of 1954) served as the Chief Justice of Delaware.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] The 46th governor of Pennsylvania, Tom Wolf; the 42nd governor of Illinois, businessman Bruce Rauner; and the 31st governor and current senator from North Dakota, John Hoeven (R), are also Dartmouth alumni.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Ernesto de la Guardia, class of 1925, was president of the Republic of Panama.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dartmouth alumni serving as CEOs or company presidents and executives include John Henry Patterson (NCR owner) and founder, Charles Alfred Pillsbury, founder of the Pillsbury Company and patriarch of the Pillsbury family, Sandy Alderson (San Diego Padres), John Donahoe (Nike, Inc.), Louis V.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Haldeman (Putnam Investments), Donald J.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] (Hallmark Cards), Douglas Hodge (CEO of PIMCO accused of fraud), Jeffrey R.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Immelt (General Electric), Gail Koziara Boudreaux (UnitedHealthcare), Grant Tinker (NBC), Greg Maffei (Liberty Media), and Brian Goldner (Hasbro).
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] In literature and journalism, Dartmouth has produced 13 Pulitzer Prize winners: Thomas M.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Burton, Richard Eberhart, Dan Fagin, Paul Gigot, Frank Gilroy, Jake Hooker, Nigel Jaquiss, Joseph Rago, Martin J.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Shipler, David Shribman, Justin Harvey Smith and Robert Frost.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Frost, who received four Pulitzer Prizes for Poetry in his lifetime, attended but did not graduate from Dartmouth; he is, however, the only person to have received two honorary degrees from Dartmouth.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Norman Maclean, professor at the University of Chicago and author of *A River Runs Through It and Other Stories*, graduated from Dartmouth in 1924.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Theodor Geisel, better known as children's author Dr.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Seuss, was a member of the class of 1925.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Tom Ryan, CEO and president of Paramount Streaming and Founder of Pluto TV graduated in 1991.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Hyrum Smith, brother of Mormon Prophet Joseph Smith, attended the college in his teens.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dartmouth alumni in academia include Stuart Kauffman and Jeffrey Weeks, both recipients of MacArthur Fellowships (commonly called "genius grants").
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dartmouth has also graduated three Nobel Prize winners with four separate prizes: Owen Chamberlain (Physics, 1959), K.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Barry Sharpless (Chemistry, 2001 and 2022), and George Davis Snell (Physiology or Medicine, 1980).
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Nine of Dartmouth's seventeen presidents were alumni of the college.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] A number of Dartmouth alumni have found success in professional sports.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] In baseball, Dartmouth alumni include All-Star and three-time Gold Glove winner and manager Brad Ausmus, All-Star reliever Mike Remlinger, , pitcher Kyle Hendricks and first baseman Ben Rice.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Professional football players include Miami Dolphins quarterback Jay Fiedler, linebacker Reggie Williams, three-time Pro Bowler Nick Lowery, quarterback Jeff Kemp, and Tennessee Titans tight end Casey Cramer, and Miami Dolphins defensive coordinator Matt Burke.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dartmouth has also produced a number of Olympic competitors.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Lawrence Whitney won bronze at the 1912 Summer Olympics in men's shot put.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Adam Nelson won the silver medal in the shot put in the 2000 Sydney Olympics and the gold medal at the 2004 Athens Olympics to go along with his gold medal in the 2005 World Championships in Athletics in Helsinki.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Kristin King and Sarah Parsons were members of the United States' 2006 bronze medal-winning ice hockey team.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Cherie Piper, Gillian Apps, and Katie Weatherston were among Canada's ice hockey gold medalists in 2006.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] At the 2024 Olympics, Ariana Ramsey won a bronze medal with the United States women's national rugby sevens team.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dick Durrance and Tim Caldwell competed for the United States in skiing in the 1936 and 1976 Winter Olympics, respectively.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Arthur Shaw, Earl Thomson, Edwin Myers, Marc Wright, Adam Nelson, Gerry Ashworth, and Vilhjálmur Einarsson have all won medals in track and field events.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Former heavyweight rower Dominic Seiterle is a member of the Canadian national rowing team and won a gold medal at the 2008 Summer Olympics in the men's 8+ event.
[src:baseball-almanac/dartmouth-college-p02] Dartmouth College has appeared in or been referenced by a number of popular media.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] Maraniss is the author of numerous books, ranging from politics to sports.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] He has written books on Green Bay Packers head coach Vince Lombardi, Baseball Hall of Famer Roberto Clemente, the 1960 Summer Olympics, and on U.S.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] Presidents Bill Clinton and Barack Obama.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] Maraniss was born in Detroit, Michigan to Elliot and Mary Maraniss.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] He attended the University of Wisconsin-Madison.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] Maraniss and his wife Linda, married in 1969 and had two children; they live in Washington, D.C. and Madison, Wisconsin.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] His son, Andrew Maraniss is also an author and was on the *New York Times* bestseller list in 2015.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] Maraniss began his career as reporter at *The Capital Times* in Madison, and later worked at the *Trenton Times*.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] For *The Washington Post*, he won the Pulitzer Prize for National Reporting in 1993, for his "revealing articles on the life and political records" of Bill Clinton, then a presidential candidate.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] He was also assigned the job of biographer for their coverage of 2008 presidential candidate, Barack Obama.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] In 2022, Maraniss published his biography Path Lit by Lightning: The Life of Jim Thorpe, which received critical acclaim for its in-depth portrayal of the legendary athlete.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] The book was recognized as a finalist for the Pulitzer Prize for History in 2023.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] Continuing his involvement in journalism and academia, Maraniss returned to Vanderbilt University in the Spring of 2024 as a distinguished visiting professor, co-teaching courses on political biography and sports and society alongside his son, Andrew Maraniss.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] He also served as a member of the jury for the 2025 Plutarch Award, presented by the Biographers International Organization.
[src:baseball-almanac/david-maraniss] In addition to his teaching and writing, Maraniss remains active in journalism, contributing articles to The Washington Post, including coverage of the 2024 U.S. presidential election.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] An **organizational founder** is a person who has undertaken some or all of the formational work needed to create a new organization, whether it is a business, a charitable organization, a governing body, a school, a group of entertainers, or any other type of organization.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] If there are multiple founders, each can be referred to as a **co-founder**.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] If the organization is a business, the founder is usually referred as an entrepreneur.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] If an organization is created to carry out charitable work, the founder is generally considered a philanthropist.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] A number of specific issues have been identified in connection with the role of the founder.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] The founder of an organization might be so closely identified with that organization, or so heavily involved in its operations, that the organization can struggle to exist without the founder's presence.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] "One practical way to cope with overreliance on a founder is to distribute management duties so that others are clearly responsible for important operations.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] If the founder is on the nonprofit's board, part of the solution is to make sure that the board is diverse, balanced, and regularly infused with new blood".
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] The language of securities regulation in the United States considers co-founders to be "promoters" under Regulation D.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] In fact, there is no formal, legal definition of what makes someone a co-founder.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] The right to call oneself a co-founder can be established through an agreement with one's fellow co-founders or with permission of the board of directors, investors, or shareholders of a startup company.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] When there is no definitive agreement, like a shareholders' agreement, disputes about who the co-founders are, can arise.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] Some organizations maintain a connection with their founder by establishing a position of **founder emeritus**, either as an entirely symbolic post, or as a position with some power, such as a permanent position on the board of directors.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] A drawback to such an arrangement is the possibility that the founder will clash with the person who has replaced them as leader of the organization, and that such a conflict will affect the performance of the founder emeritus as a board member.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] In some instances, the desire of the founder to maintain control over the organization becomes a problem because, when an entrepreneurial organization is successful, "[i]t outgrows the ability of the founder, or even of a small team around the founder, to control".
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] The *Harvard Business Review* identified this problem as the founder's dilemma, noting that in most successful companies, the founder is pushed out of control by investors within the first few years after the formation of the company.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] In some cases, a company may have multiple founders, and a prominent source of conflict can be disagreements between these founders as the company evolves.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] There are factors beyond the personality and professional accolades of a startup founder that impact the ability of a company to succeed, like trouble in funding, sudden market shutdown, not having the right team or poor scaling plan.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] Another problem that can arise is that of the forgotten founder, a person who participates early on in the formation of an enterprise, but leaves or is ousted before it achieves success, and then returns to claim a legal right to equity, intellectual property, or some other fruits of that success.
[src:baseball-almanac/organizational-founder] To avoid this problem, it is advised that the entity "incorporate early and issue shares that are subject to vesting over time".
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper was born on October 17, 1959, in Chicago, Illinois, one of four children to Robert and Margaret (née Slobatec) Roeper.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] His family came from a working-class background.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] At the age of 6, his family moved in to the south suburb of Dolton, Illinois, living at the intersection of 156th Street and Maryland Avenue.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He learned to drive at the age of 15 in the nearby Almar Plaza lot under his parents' guidance.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper attended Thornridge High School in Dolton, graduating in 1978.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] During his high school years, Roeper discovered his passion for writing, determining early on that it suited him far better than subjects like math and science.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Following high school, he enrolled at Illinois State University in Normal, Illinois where he pursued studies in mass communication.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper's university experience emphasized practical training in media, most notably active participation on the student radio station WZND-LP.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] There, he received mentorship from advisor Dwight Brooks, who provided feedback on vocal techniques such as breath control and delivery, helping to build Roeper's foundational skills in broadcasting and reporting that would support his future professional pursuits in journalism.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He graduated in 1982 with a bachelor's degree in journalism.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] During this time, he auditioned for the movie review program *Sneak Previews* when Gene Siskel and Roger Ebert (his future co-host on *At the Movies*) left the program, for which he was turned down.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper joined the *Chicago Sun-Times* as an editorial assistant in the features department in 1986.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He initially did freelancing columns before advancing to his role as a news reporter.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In his early years, Roeper covered a range of general news and local events, while developing a particular focus on sports, including extensive reporting on the Chicago White Sox that reflected his lifelong fandom.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] His assignments as a cityside reporter involved shifting between beats to build a broad understanding of Chicago, encompassing everything from neighborhood changes to cultural happenings, which honed his observational skills.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In the late 1980s, Roeper transitioned to a general-interest columnist, becoming full-time in 1988 and expanding to four columns per week by late 1989.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Notable examples from this period include pieces on urban life, such as his July 1989 column "When the changing neighborhood is yours," a personal reflection on gentrification's impact in Chicago, and lighter takes on pop culture, like analyzing the stylistic quirks in a mayor's public speeches.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Other columns ranged from politics to media to entertainment.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] During his first decade at the paper, Roeper's writing style evolved to emphasize humor and accessibility, drawing from personal anecdotes to connect with a younger, MTV-generation readership through clear, simple language and self-deprecating insights into everyday callowness.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] This approach, evident in his syndicated Sunday features column that reached over 100 papers by the early 1990s, prioritized relatable commentary on modern life over dense reporting.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In addition, Roeper has been voted the best columnist in Illinois by the Associated Press on numerous occasions.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He has also written seven books on topics ranging from movies to urban legends to conspiracy theories to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In 2009, Roeper appeared on Howard Stern's show and said he had written a book on gambling, entitled *Bet the House*, which was released in the first quarter of 2010.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper was a radio host on WLS AM 890 in Chicago.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He also hosted shows on WLUP-FM, WLS-FM, and WMVP-AM in Chicago.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In the early 2000s, he was the film critic for CBS in Chicago for three years.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] His columns have been syndicated by *The New York Times* to worldwide publications.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper has written for a number of magazines, including *Esquire*, *Spy*, *TV Guide*, *Playboy*, *Maxim*, and *Entertainment Weekly*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In 2001, he was named one of *People* magazine's most eligible bachelors.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper has been a frequent guest on *The Tonight Show*, *Live with Regis and Kelly*, *The O'Reilly Factor*, and countless other national programs.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He also hosted *Starz Inside*, a monthly documentary series that aired on the Starz network.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper appeared on the first episode of the fifth season of *Entourage*, where he reviewed a fake movie titled *Medellin* with Michael Phillips on *At the Movies*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In April 2008, Roeper was the central figure on an episode of *Top Chef*, where contestants served up movie-themed dishes to Roeper and his friends (including Aisha Tyler).
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In February 2009, Roeper launched his website, which features movie reviews, blog entries, photos, and Twitter posts.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In December 2009, he launched a video section that featured on-camera reviews of movies.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] The video segments were originally produced in partnership with the Starz premium cable channel.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper announced that the reviews would appear first on his site, then on the Starz channel.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In December 2009, it was reported that Roeper had signed with ReelzChannel to be a regular contributor.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Beginning in December 2010, Roeper began producing video reviews for ReelzChannel.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He stopped reviewing movies for ReelzChannel in February 2015; his final review was for the Jude Law disaster film *Black Sea*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] From April 12, 2010, to October 7, 2014, he co-hosted *The Roe & Roeper Show* with Roe Conn on Chicago's WLS 890 radio station from 2-6 pm CST.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In October 2015, Roeper joined the cast of the Fox Chicago morning TV show *Good Day Chicago*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He signed off from that morning TV show on October 18, 2017.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] From 2018 until 2021, he was a contributor to *Windy City Live* and from 2021 onward, a contributor to its predecessor, *Windy City Weekend*, for WLS-TV.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper was suspended from the *Sun-Times* on January 29, 2018, pending an investigation into allegations that he had purchased Twitter followers.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] On February 2, the *Sun-Times* released a statement stating that their investigation did find that Roeper purchased over 25,000 fake followers.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] The paper later reinstated him, though he was required to begin using a new account on which he was explicitly disallowed from buying followers.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In November 2025, Roeper provided a voiceover for a Mr.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Submarine 50th anniversary ad campaign, reviewing humorously one of the chain's subs as part of a series featuring Chicago notables.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In the mid-1990's, Roeper assumed the role of film critic at the *Chicago Sun-Times*, initially filling in for Roger Ebert on film reviews while continuing his general column work.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] His contributions grew beginning in 1999, as Roeper took on more dedicated film duties, including daily reviews that were nationally syndicated through the newspaper's network.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] By the early 2000s, Roeper had established himself as a key voice in print film criticism, producing consistent coverage of new releases that reached readers across the United States.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] After Gene Siskel of *Siskel & Ebert* died on February 20, 1999, Roger Ebert co-hosted the show with nearly 30 guest critics.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] After ten appearances on the program, Roeper was offered the opportunity to co-host the popular film review show with Ebert permanently.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] The series was renamed *Ebert & Roeper and the Movies* in 2000.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] The title was shortened to *Ebert & Roeper* in 2001.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Before this, he conducted an interview in 1995 with Siskel and Ebert to commemorate the 20th anniversary of their partnership.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Beginning in August 2006, while his co-host Roger Ebert was recovering from cancer surgery, Roeper was joined by numerous guest critics, including *Clerks* director Kevin Smith, *The Tonight Show* host Jay Leno, and singer-songwriter John Mellencamp.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] On Sunday, July 20, 2008, Roeper announced that he was leaving the show in mid-August and would return with a new show later in the year.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] However, plans for a new program starring Roeper failed to materialize.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Between 2009 and late 2010, Roeper contributed video reviews to Starz.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In December 2010, he moved to ReelzChannel, where he contributed a segment titled *Richard Roeper's Reviews* every weekday at 5:00 pm ET.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper remained with the network until early 2015.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In early 2013, Roeper began contributing film reviews to *RogerEbert.com*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] On September 12, 2013, it was announced that Roeper would replace Roger Ebert as the main movie critic for the *Chicago Sun-Times* after his death on April 4, 2013, at the age of 70.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In August 2014, Roeper became first-string film critic for the *Chicago Sun-Times*, where he made his debut reviewing *Guardians of the Galaxy*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] During this time, he expanded daily reviews to include TV and streaming content while maintaining syndication.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He is a member of Chicago Film Critics Association.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Since 2021, he has hosted a podcast entitled *The Richard Roeper Show* (formerly *Screen Time with Roe and Roeper* which he hosted with Roe Conn until 2022) for American Eagle, which airs every Tuesday and Thursday.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In 2025, the program evolved to address timely issues, most notably an October 2025 episode dissecting the NBA gambling scandal involving figures like Jontay Porter and its broader implications of sports betting integrity.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] On March 19, 2025, Roeper revealed that he accepted a buyout from the *Sun-Times* to terminate his employment, ending his time at the newspaper after a 39-year run.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Despite this, he is expected to keep reviewing movies on his podcast and for *Windy City Weekend* on WLS-TV.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper's last review for the *Sun-Times*, published on March 20, 2025, was for *Snow White*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In 2025, Roeper became a regular contributor to *RogerEbert.com*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Later that same year in October, he launched the podcast *The Movie of Your Life* which explores connections between life experiences and beloved films.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] The series premiered on October 17, 2025, with a November 3 episode featuring an in-depth discussion with Chaz Ebert on her preservation of Roger Ebert's legacy, the evolution of film criticism, and the influential movies in their lives.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper's review methodology emphasized accessibility and balance, blending detailed analysis with a conversational tone to appeal to a broad audience.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He adopted the four-star rating system traditional to his job at the *Chicago Sun-Times*, where four stars denoted exceptional films and one star indicated significant flaws, often highlighting narrative strengths, performances, and cultural relevance.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] While inheriting the thumbs-up/down binary from the *Siskel & Ebert* tradition, Roeper primarily used it in supplementary contexts, focusing in print on nuanced critiques that covered both mainstream blockbusters and independent cinema.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] His approach prioritized conceptual insights, such as a film's emotional impact or innovative storytelling, over exhaustive technical breakdowns.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Among his notable reviews, Roeper praised the innovative structure of Christopher Nolan's 2000 film *Memento*, awarding it four stars for its reverse-chronological narrative and psychological depth, which helped elevate its profile as an indie thriller.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Similarly, his enthusiastic four-star endorsement of Ang Lee's 2000 film *Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon* underscored its blend of martial arts spectacle and emotional resonance, contributing to its mainstream breakthrough and Oscar success.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper also championed Chicago-centric films, such as revisiting the 1986 John Hughes film *Ferris Bueller's Day Off* in later articles where he described it as a "suicide prevention film" through its themes of friendship and resilience, thereby promoting the city's cinematic heritage.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] These reviews exemplified his role in bridging local culture with national discourse, often spotlighting indie projects and regional filmmakers to foster the Chicago cinema scene.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper has cited *The Maltese Falcon*, *The Godfather* trilogy, and *Ferris Bueller's Day Off* as among his favorite films.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] On *The Godfather* trilogy, Roeper highlighted its epic scope, character-driven drama, and groundbreaking blend of family saga with crime thriller elements that redefined the gangster genre.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] He has noted the trilogy's enduring impact through its exploration of power, loyalty, and betrayal, calling the first two films the pinnacle of director Francis Ford Coppola's work.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] On *Ferris Bueller's Day Off*, the film holds a special place for him due to its Chicago setting, which resonates with his local roots, praising it for its innovative, joyful take on teenage rebellion and breaking the fourth wall.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In a 2009 retrospective, Roeper stated that, "It has one of the highest 'repeatability' factors of any film I've ever seen...I can watch it again and again.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] That's the lasting message of *Ferris Bueller's Day Off*." In addition, in a 2016 retrospective, Roeper appreciated the film's narrative flair and Matthew Broderick's charismatic performance as emblematic of John Hughes' influnence on 1980's comedy.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper pays homage to the film with a license plate that says "SVFRRIS".
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In a 2000 interview, he cited Woody Allen as a hero of filmmaking.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Among his favorite films from the 1990s are *Goodfellas*, *Pulp Fiction*, *Heat*, *Good Will Hunting*, and *Notting Hill*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] In November 2004, on a special segment of *Ebert & Roeper*, Roeper stated that his all-time favorite film about Thanksgiving is *Planes, Trains and Automobiles*.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Since 2000, Roeper has compiled an annual film list which provides an overview of his critical preferences.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] Roeper is an avid fan of the Chicago White Sox, having been obsessed before he was born when his mother was nine months pregnant with him during the team's 1959 World Series loss, an event that ignited his lifelong fandom in a city dominated by supporters of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:baseball-almanac/richard-roeper] This passion grew through local neighborhood games, including playing Little League baseball in Dolton, Illinois.
